{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17612785","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17612785"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T14:27:29+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T14:27:29+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16286"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16286","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16286"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8977"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115938"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8977","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8977"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16286"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97937"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"5586"},{"type":"tags","id":"7244"},{"type":"tags","id":"7482"},{"type":"tags","id":"8406"},{"type":"tags","id":"8558"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21360"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21363"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115938","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115938"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe external auditory canal extends from the external ear to the tympanic membrane. It has distinct anatomical regions with different tissue compositions.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the composition of the external auditory canal?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Medial two-thirds bony, lateral one-third cartilaginous","Medial half bony, lateral half cartilaginous","Medial one-third bony, lateral two-thirds cartilaginous","Medial two-thirds cartilaginous, lateral one-third bony","Medial one-third cartilaginous, lateral two-thirds bony"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe external auditory canal is composed of \u003Cstrong\u003Emedial two-thirds bony and lateral one-third cartilaginous\u003C/strong\u003E portions. The bony portion is formed by the tympanic part of the temporal bone, while the cartilaginous portion contains ceruminous glands and hair follicles.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMedial half bony, lateral half cartilaginous\u003C/strong\u003E understates the bony portion. \u003Cstrong\u003EMedial one-third bony, lateral two-thirds cartilaginous\u003C/strong\u003E reverses the correct proportions. \u003Cstrong\u003EMedial two-thirds cartilaginous, lateral one-third bony\u003C/strong\u003E reverses the tissue types. \u003Cstrong\u003EMedial one-third cartilaginous, lateral two-thirds bony\u003C/strong\u003E reverses both the tissue types and proportions. Understanding these proportions is clinically relevant for procedures such as ear examination and foreign body removal, as the cartilaginous portion can be manipulated while the bony portion is rigid.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The external auditory canal is approximately one-third cartilaginous laterally and two-thirds bony medially.","The cartilaginous portion contains ceruminous glands that produce earwax and hair follicles.","The bony portion is formed by the tympanic part of the temporal bone."],"references":["Benson JC, Lane JI. Temporal Bone Anatomy. Neuroimaging Clin N Am. 2022 Nov;32(4):763-775. doi: 10.1016/j.nic.2022.07.010. Epub 2022 Sep 21. PMID: 36244722.","Netter, F. H. (2015). Netter\u0027s Cranial Nerve Collection E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Singh, V. (2024). Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022). The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97937"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16286"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97937","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97937"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-26T15:42:13+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-26T15:42:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8977"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115938"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4930","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4930"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Nervous System","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-27T10:23:42+10: